Cognitively, the presence of two targets leads to a dual-target search scenario~\citep{fleck2010generalized}, which effectively introduces a `masking' effect where the mor salient target is selected and the search for more targets stops (``satisfaction of search"), i.e.\ people tend to pick the more salient target and not notice the second target, even though in the absence of the more salient target they would have picked it out. 
